76561197993284064,Recommended,291010,12397163,"Posted: 7 October, 2014",all,GarGhuul,"I played a game like this back in April, called Daylight.While that game seems to have had a higher budget, they both accomplish the same thing fairly effectively. The gameplay is quite similar.Basically you need to find the pages of the daughter's journal in a randomly generated hospital-shaped maze... which redraws itself.While you do this, there is a creature called ""Hatman"" who tries to catch you.There are also smaller shadow-people which can be banished with a flashlight.The catch is: Using the flashlight attracts the Hatman.Not a bad game, and it tries to do a few things that are quite difficult to do. Mostly get things to happen in the right order, with the player looking in the right place at the right time... without forcing them to.As with Daylight, the results are mixed. Mind you I am not aware of any game which has pulled that off without issues.A fun ride, if a bit short... which is good otherwise you'd become used to it.Don't look too hard at it and just enjoy the playthrough. Sort of like a made-for-TV horror movie.Popcorn optional."
,Not Recommended,291010,28459316,"Posted: 18 December, 2016",all,Iamfishyfishy,"If you were looking for a good horror game, don't even consider this game. Not only are the graphics absolute trash, but the whole game seems to revolve around collecting the remaining two pages in the rooms and finding items. Finding the items is an absolute nightmare and I only managed to find the crowbar, matches and a spike pit featured in the trailer video, all in one hour. That is literally how long it takes sometimes due to poor game design and repetitive room layouts. The room layout is so repetitive you easily lose your way and have difficulty even telling where you are, it's essentially a walking, searching and escaping simulator all mashed up into one. Not to mention the AI for the Hat Man is atrocious, since all it does is ""teleport"" to a location directly in your field of view, namely in front of you. He goes through walls and can't be shaken off, as he'll just ""teleport"" directly in front of you again when you have all five pages of the journal. He looks like some image taken from google and plastered onto a model and called the oh-so-scary Hat Man.As for the Shadow people, I never even encountered any of them. The only thing I'd seen that would even possibly be close to that was at the beginning when you click on the journal and a creature shows up to steal your soul, but I think even then that's just the Hat Man. It's a bit like Dead by Daylight, Slender: The Eight Pages and Vanish all combined to make this pathetic excuse for a game. You walk away and instantly the rooms have changed, making it impossible to find your way back. Some hints or even an explanation of what to do would be nice so I'm not aimlessly wandering around halls, running from the dreaded Hat Man, who's kill animation makes me want to throw up.Shockingly enough, the audio and atmosphere in the game was tolerable. Audio would get extremely repetitive, but the occasional radio playing badly done music was fairly creepy. Also a falling tile or light, whatever it was, was a good trick, but the novelty wears off really quick and you grow to expect it. Same for the mysteriously moving wheelchairs, although those can get you caught if you're unlucky (Or daft).So overall, this game isn't really something you should buy, especially at full price. If you're really that desperate to try it, wait until it goes on sale, that way you won't be as disapointed. I'm disgusted people say it's a quality game and recommend it, as a troll or not, because this is worse than Rob Zombie's '31'. And that movie was terrible. Really, if you want a quality game that still has the room changing mechanic, install Vanish on GameJolt, it's good and free."
