,Not Recommended,291010,15748243,"Posted: 8 May, 2015",all,Sturmgeist,"The sad part is... I've played scarier games for free. I'm pretty sure this *isn't* the scariest game of 2014.This *was* a fifteen dollar game that made Daylight look good. It's dropped to five and I suppose that's more reasonable than Daylight.The game itself is an obvious Slender clone, where you're running around grabbing pages while avoiding the monster. Unlike slender, however, the monster doesn't ever teleport. No, he just follows you around endlessly, and phases through walls. So if you get cornered, you may as well die then because I waited five minutes staring at him while crouched with no movement, whatsoever. It would seem like a breath of fresh air, since you can obviously outrun but not hide from the Hat Man, unlike in recent horror games where hiding is key. In this, you're running around to get pages with no places to hide, much like slender.The voice acting is pretty hilarious(ly bad), but the sound quality is alright. This really is just your average run-of-the-mill indie-horror game, with the same graphics, same UI, and same gameplay, except it's longer. Oh, and the layout of the hospital changes. It doesn't exactly randomize scares like Daylight, so there's not as much replay value (which implies loosely that there is some small replay value to Daylight, which is up to your interpretation)If it were any shorter than it already is it wouldn't qualify for the price it has. If it were any longer, I'd be♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥and begging myself that this goddamn game would be over.All in all, it's a fun... half-hour, and I can say it was worth the 19 cents I paid for it. maybe even worth $1.50-2.00.I can recommend the game to you, but not at the price. In fact, almost any price, unless you want to do it to support the devs. The game itself is really not worth it."
