,Not Recommended,291010,33635103,Posted: 18 July,all,Bob,"I don’t enjoy being scared but I do enjoy creepy atmospheric games with engaging and mysterious stories. So I occasionally buy horror games in the hope of finding something like the good Silent Hill games but sometimes I end up buying games as dire as this one.On my first attempt, right near the start I picked up the diary and immediately died. Okay so I assumed that was not what I was supposed to do. After scouring the rest of the room I found out I was supposed to pick up the diary but just the game had spawned an enemy right in my face.Having got past that hurdle I was able to start the game properly. I’m the type of person who when they play a game they wants to explore all the game has to offer so I tend to look round the whole area before moving on. So I started methodically exploring the level and quickly got frustrated as I kept stumbling onto things to progress the game but there were so many avenues I hadn't explored. The same rooms were reused over and again so there was no way to keep track of where I had been without a map. Only at this point did I realise that the map was not fixed it just procedurally generates the map using the same handful of rooms. Upon realising this I lost any remaining interest in the game. All there was left to do was aimlessly wander through the same rooms over and again till the things you need to progress appear.In the latter part of the game the enemies move faster and spawn closer to you. So whether you win or lose felt entirely arbitrary, depending on how the items and enemies spawn and nothing to do with the players input.The one thing I did like was the voice actor playing your daughter, she did a good job. This then directly contrasts with the voice actor of the mother. She is so bad I honestly wasn't sure if she was a voice synthesizer at first.All in all the only saving grace of this game is that I bought it in the sale for 19p but still I could spent that on something useful like an onion."
